.TH "TAKO" "1" "Jun 2026" "Tako CLI" "Tako CLI Manual"

.SH NAME
tako-destroy - Remove deployed application and optionally clean up app-owned leftovers


.SH SYNOPSIS
\fBtako destroy [flags]\fP


.SH DESCRIPTION
Destroy the deployed application runtime and clean up app-owned resources.

.PP
This command has two modes:
.IP "  1." 5
DECOMMISSION MODE (default):
.RS
.IP \(bu 2
Stops and removes application service replicas
.IP \(bu 2
Removes application service images
.IP \(bu 2
Removes deployment files
.IP \(bu 2
Keeps tako-proxy, logs, and server setup
.IP \(bu 2
Safe for production - can redeploy later
.RE
.IP "  2." 5
PURGE MODE (--purge-all):
.RS
.IP \(bu 2
Everything from decommission mode, PLUS:
.IP \(bu 2
Prunes unused app-owned volumes
.IP \(bu 2
Prunes stopped app containers and old app images
.IP \(bu 2
Keeps shared takod and tako-proxy runtime intact
.IP \(bu 2
Safe when unrelated projects share the same node
.RE

.PP
Safety Features:
   - Production servers require explicit confirmation
   - Shows what will be removed before proceeding
   - Use --force to skip confirmation prompts

.PP
Examples:
   tako destroy                    # Decommission app, keep server setup
   tako destroy --purge-all        # Also prune app-owned leftovers
   tako destroy --force            # Skip confirmation prompts

.PP
PURGE MODE is app/stage scoped. It does not remove shared takod or tako-proxy.


.SH OPTIONS
\fB--force\fP[=false]
	Skip confirmation prompts

.PP
\fB-h\fP, \fB--help\fP[=false]
	help for destroy

.PP
\fB--purge-all\fP[=false]
	Also prune app-owned leftovers after decommission


.SH OPTIONS INHERITED FROM PARENT COMMANDS
\fB--config\fP=""
	config file (default is ./tako.yaml or ./tako.json)

.PP
\fB-e\fP, \fB--env\fP=""
	environment to deploy (default: production or only environment)

.PP
\fB--events\fP=""
	stream progress events to stdout: ndjson (human output moves to stderr)

.PP
\fB--host-key-mode\fP=""
	SSH host key verification mode: tofu, strict, ask (default: tofu)

.PP
\fB--output\fP="text"
	output format: text or json (json reserves stdout for the final result document)

.PP
\fB-v\fP, \fB--verbose\fP[=false]
	verbose output


.SH SEE ALSO
\fBtako(1)\fP
